                                      <handDesc>
                                         <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                                            <seg type="script"><date>Mid-nineteenth/mid-twentieth century bulky script.</date></seg>
                                            <seg type="ink">Black (on many folia brownish); vivid red.</seg>
                                            <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; directives for the ministers;
                                              titles of books to be read; elements of the punctuation signs;
                                               elements of the Ethiopic numerals. On the incipit page of <ref target="#p1_i1">Text 1</ref>, <locus target="#8r"/>
                                               two first lines of each column are rubricated. Rubrication has been carefully executed in the main
                                               hand, probably along with the writing of the main text.</seg>
                                               <desc>Careful but irregular; by a poorly trained scribe. Broad, upright or slightly
                                                 right sloping script. Downstrokes slanted irregulary, horizontal tops.
                                                 Rectangular letter shapes, but irregular and poorly drawn.
                                              Starting from ca. <locus target="#47"/>, the handwriting becomes even less careful;
                                              on <locus from="50r" to="51r"/> the scribe reduced the size of the script
                                              and accomodated on the pages
                                              more written lines than the ruling allows.
                                              It cannot be excluded that more than one scribe participated in copying.
                                               </desc>
                                         </handNote>
